git init

Initialize a new Git repository.
Syntax: git init [project-name]
git clone

Clone a repository into a new directory.
Syntax: git clone <repository-url> [directory]
git add

Add file contents to the index (staging area).
Syntax: git add <file>
git commit

Record changes to the repository.
Syntax: git commit -m "Commit message"
git status

Show the working tree status.
Syntax: git status
git diff

Show changes between commits, commit and working tree, etc.
Syntax: git diff [commit]
git log

Show the commit logs.
Syntax: git log
git branch

List, create, or delete branches.
Syntax: git branch, git branch <branch-name>
git checkout

Switch branches or restore working tree files.
Syntax: git checkout <branch-name>, git checkout -- <file>
git merge

Join two or more development histories together.
Syntax: git merge <branch-name>
git remote

Manage set of tracked repositories.
Syntax: git remote add <remote-name> <repository-url>
git fetch

Download objects and refs from another repository.
Syntax: git fetch <remote-name>
git pull

Fetch from and integrate with another repository or a local branch.
Syntax: git pull <remote-name> <branch-name>
git push

Update remote refs along with associated objects.
Syntax: git push <remote-name> <branch-name>
git rm

Remove files from the working tree and from the index.
Syntax: git rm <file>

git mv

Move or rename a file, a directory, or a symlink.
Syntax: git mv <source> <destination>
git stash

Stash the changes in a dirty working directory away.
Syntax: git stash, git stash apply
git tag

Create, list, delete, or verify a tag object signed with GPG.
Syntax: git tag -a <tag-name> -m "Tag message"

git reset

Reset current HEAD to the specified state.
Syntax: git reset [--soft | --mixed | --hard] <commit>
git rebase

Forward-port local commits to the updated upstream head.
Syntax: git rebase <branch-name>
